{"focus":{"id":"b686895b-8c12-52ff-84c5-1acd55ee9e34","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba0609c-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"8.EE.C.7","description":"Solve linear equations in one variable.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["8"],"grade":"8","domain":"EE","cluster":"8.EE.C","level":"standard"},"ancestors":[],"descendants":[{"id":"78d6afb1-5683-570f-9e44-8f3a1041b452","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9efd43-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSA-CED.A.4","description":"Rearrange formulas to highlight a quantity of interest, using the same reasoning as in solving equations. *For example, rearrange Ohm's law $V = IR$ to highlight resistance $R$.*","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"A-CED","cluster":"HSA-CED.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"9ffcdbe8-b64e-5d69-b1cb-1a1c9f330d8a","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9c57c7-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSA-REI.A.1","description":"Explain each step in solving a simple equation as following from the equality of numbers asserted at the previous step, starting from the assumption that the original equation has a solution. Construct a viable argument to justify a solution method.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"A-REI","cluster":"HSA-REI.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"5b23724f-8107-5584-b681-0062e78a939e","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9e5ed4-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSA-REI.B.3","description":"Solve linear equations and inequalities in one variable, including equations with coefficients represented by letters.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"A-REI","cluster":"HSA-REI.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"115f86cd-46ac-576c-9d89-ac5f793ebe03","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9d91e7-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSA-REI.A.2","description":"Solve simple rational and radical equations in one variable, and give examples showing how extraneous solutions may arise.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"A-REI","cluster":"HSA-REI.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"8d469405-0fa7-5fc8-86f7-174b02fc1588","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba1507e-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSA-REI.B.4.a","description":"Use the method of completing the square to transform any quadratic equation in x into an equation of the form $(x - p)^{2} = q$ that has the same solutions. Derive the quadratic formula from this form.","statementType":"Component","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"A-REI","cluster":"HSA-REI.B","level":"substandard"},{"id":"3b81e97d-948b-546b-859a-cbcffd5558cd","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba1d10e-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSA-REI.B.4.b","description":"Solve quadratic equations by inspection (e.g., for $x^{2} = 49$), taking square roots, completing the square, the quadratic formula and factoring, as appropriate to the initial form of the equation. Recognize when the quadratic formula gives complex solutions and write them as a ± bi for real numbers a and b.","statementType":"Component","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"A-REI","cluster":"HSA-REI.B","level":"substandard"},{"id":"09ae5d13-9211-58d4-88a2-f42b6d755699","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9c54a3-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSA-CED.A.1","description":"Create equations and inequalities in one variable and use them to solve problems. Include equations arising from linear and quadratic functions, and simple rational and exponential functions.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"A-CED","cluster":"HSA-CED.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"dd015436-cfc6-59ea-b0de-4053e38a40ff","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9f04ba-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSF-BF.B.4","description":"Find inverse functions.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"F-BF","cluster":"HSF-BF.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"b517efad-0cfa-5eb1-994f-70cb48476ba9","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9c73d2-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-GPE.A.1","description":"Derive the equation of a circle of given center and radius using the Pythagorean Theorem; complete the square to find the center and radius of a circle given by an equation.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-GPE","cluster":"HSG-GPE.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"d7e1d5de-d82c-5489-a1f3-38fc49b7f9b0","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba0f6fa-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSN-CN.C.9","description":"(+) Know the Fundamental Theorem of Algebra; show that it is true for quadratic polynomials.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"N-CN","cluster":"HSN-CN.C","level":"standard"},{"id":"9354b4ae-34f1-5768-9f99-07b5c9292ee4","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba155d1-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSA-SSE.B.3.a","description":"Factor a quadratic expression to reveal the zeros of the function it defines.","statementType":"Component","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"A-SSE","cluster":"HSA-SSE.B","level":"substandard"},{"id":"3673e4d3-33a5-57f5-91f5-8ed8ec73be0f","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba06a30-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSA-REI.C.7","description":"Solve a simple system consisting of a linear equation and a quadratic equation in two variables algebraically and graphically. *For example, find the points of intersection between the line $y = -3x$ and the circle $x^{2} + y^{2} = 3$.*","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"A-REI","cluster":"HSA-REI.C","level":"standard"},{"id":"8ff8661c-a3d0-50ba-9876-e9b2432cb761","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9f920f-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSF-BF.B.5","description":"(+) Understand the inverse relationship between exponents and logarithms and use this relationship to solve problems involving logarithms and exponents.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"F-BF","cluster":"HSF-BF.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"8e1de64e-487f-5145-a1ea-cf51f433d2b7","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9f16e0-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-GPE.B.4","description":"Use coordinates to prove simple geometric theorems algebraically. *For example, prove or disprove that a figure defined by four given points in the coordinate plane is a rectangle; prove or disprove that the point $(1, \\sqrt{3})$ lies on the circle centered at the origin and containing the point (0, 2).*","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-GPE","cluster":"HSG-GPE.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"f7cc5a71-2d54-5197-9757-3b99d3b468a9","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9d8c97-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSA-APR.B.2","description":"Know and apply the Remainder Theorem: For a polynomial p(x) and a number a, the remainder on division by x - a is p(a), so p(a) = 0 if and only if (x - a) is a factor of p(x).","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"A-APR","cluster":"HSA-APR.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"897aefc4-aadd-5681-b5cb-20ae995b6dfb","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9e5a39-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSA-APR.B.3","description":"Identify zeros of polynomials when suitable factorizations are available, and use the zeros to construct a rough graph of the function defined by the polynomial.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"A-APR","cluster":"HSA-APR.B","level":"standard"}],"learningComponents":[{"id":"a7ca2ced-e4d9-5094-9637-286665046547","description":"Solve linear equations in one variable.","author":"Achievement Network","provider":"Learning Commons"}],"edges":[{"id":"bd1b8cc4-4ede-5db0-8383-36c03a8baebe","label":"buildsTowards","source":"b686895b-8c12-52ff-84c5-1acd55ee9e34","target":"78d6afb1-5683-570f-9e44-8f3a1041b452"},{"id":"88923a97-b100-5d9d-9bc5-66ec92047d25","label":"buildsTowards","source":"b686895b-8c12-52ff-84c5-